metas is a metaphor from the Roman circus. The goal or turning-point was a group of three conical columns, raised on a basement at the end of the barrier (spina), round which the cllariots turned. There were two metae, one at each extremity of the spina, called meta prima and meta seczmda (Dictionary of Aoztc‘qm'ties). Here the word is applied to Pachynus, the southern cape of Sicily, round which the ships must turn to reach Italy by the longer route.
